	abstract = {The evolutionary causes of sexual dimorphism in plants have not been as widely studied as in animals and the importance of sexual selection in causing dimorphism remains controversial. Sexual selection is most obvious when it favours the evolution of a trait which enhances mating success at the expense of decreased viability. We studied the relationship between ¯oral display (number of in¯orescences), pollinator attraction and plant survival in a dioecious shrub, Leucadendron xanthoconus. Pollinator attraction, measured as the number of insect pollinators, increased linearly with ¯oral display in males. However, males with extravagant displays had a higher probability of dying. Our data suggest that male plants are undergoing selection on ¯oral display for increased mating success counterbalanced by selection against plants with extravagant displays. Seed set in females did not increase with ¯oral display, except at very low in¯orescence numbers. Nor was female survival correlated with ¯oral display. Because in¯orescences are terminal in the species, selection for more in¯orescences in males causes increased rami®cation, thinner terminal branches and smaller leaves. Thus vegetative dimorphism in this species appears to be caused by selection for extravagant ¯oral display in males, but not females. Limits to dimorphism are imposed by survival costs of elaborate display.},
